description:
Jerry Seinfeld returns to the garage for a classic Porsche extravaganza! The guys cover Jerry's insane 10-year 907 restoration, review his 1979 Porsche 928, debate modern Japanese cars, and talk about his HBO project with Larry David.

Jerry's 907 showcases an incredible 10-year restoration journey, returning this ultra-rare race car (only a handful exist worldwide) to its original glory, complete with period-correct details like the illuminated number panel and ice box for the driver's cool suit. The car has significant racing heritage, having won the 1968 Daytona 24-hour race with Vic Elford at the wheel.

The episode also features Jerry's stunning Minerva Blue 1979 Porsche 928, featuring the unique blue Pasha interior and the iconic 4.5-liter V8 engine. Jerry's enthusiasm for the car's revolutionary design is contagious as he describes driving it as "being like a police dog attacking a foam-protected arm."

The hosts also dive into YouTube inspiration from a Volvo rescue, debate their favorite Japanese cars (with Jerry expressing surprising interest in the new Honda Accord), and share personal stories about first cars and daily carry items.

title: Man Buys 4 FLOODED CARS for $2,150 and RESTORES them Back to New | by @MrZhangsDetailing
description:
How do you recover a car that seems to be in the last minute? Sometimes you just have to brush it a little. Still, this is more than a simple detailing work.

But Mr. Zhang doesnâ€™t just clean cars. He revives what people gave up on. He doesnâ€™t detail, he confronts. The man steps into cabins full of rot, rust, liquefied regret, and calls it work. No mask thick enough. No gloves tough enough. Just a pressure washer, a pair of lungs, and the unspoken conviction that even a flooded, fermented, mud-choked machine still deserves a second chance.


A $300 swamp coffin, where mold grows faster than hope. A Mitsubishi that tried to become a mountain. A soy-sauced sedan soaked in the leftovers of someoneâ€™s culinary empire. And a BMW 7 Series (the luxury lie) dressed in dried filth like a pharaoh in desert-wrappings. Each one dead on arrival. Each one rolled in like a wheeled sin. Each one whispering: "You canâ€™t fix me".

And this is simply what he did. Because he always does.

title: Lambo Revuelto v 1000hp tuned BMWs: DRAG RACE
description:
Change your car with Carwow: https://bit.ly/Change-Your-Car-0612

Whoâ€™s ready for the greatest BMW drag race EVER?! 

Weâ€™ve got our hands on a whole host of tuned BMWs, and theyâ€™re about to go head-to-head against each other (along with a host of supercars) to find out which tuned BMW is best! 

In terms of the BMWs on show, thereâ€™s a whole host of them. Weâ€™re kicking things off with an M140i & a M240i, and then weâ€™ll run through the cars in order of power, including an M2, an X3M, two new M5s, several M3s and an M4! All of these contenders have been tuned, with power outputs ranging from 445hp through to an eye-watering 1,300hp! 

However, itâ€™s not just BMWs on show today. Weâ€™ve also brought along a host of supercars to give these BMWs a true test. The first is a Lamborghini Huracan Performante, which houses a 5.2-litre naturally aspirated V10 producing 640hp and 600Nm. This power is sent to all four wheels through a 7-speed dual-clutch transmission, and it weighs just 1,482kg. 

Once the Huracan tastes defeat, weâ€™ll wheel in a McLaren 750S. This is powered by a 4-litre twin-turbo V8 that produces 750hp and 800Nm, sent to the rear wheels via a 7-speed dual-clutch gearbox. Itâ€™s also super light, weighing in at 1,440kg.

Finally, weâ€™ve got another Lamborghini to face off against the most powerful cars on show - a Revuelto!  It rolls up with a 6.5-litre naturally-aspirated V12 and three electric motors. Combined, they can put down 1,015hp and 1,062Nm. The car comes with all-wheel drive, and it tips the scales at just under 2 tonnes!

So, how will this one play out - will several of the tuned cars break down? And will any of them be able to topple the mighty Revuelto?! Thereâ€™s only one way to find out for sureâ€¦ LETâ€™S RACE!

The Maruti Suzuki Victoris is the newest mid-size SUV in India, designed to take on popular rivals like the Hyundai Creta, Kia Seltos, Grand Vitara and Toyota Hyryder. With its aggressive pricing and long list of premium features, it promises to be one of the most talked-about launches of 2025.

In this detailed video, we cover everything you need to know about the Victoris â€” from its design and interiors to features, engine options, mileage, safety tech and prices.

Highlights of the Maruti Victoris:

Exterior & Design: Bold SUV styling, panoramic sunroof, sharp LED lights, muscular wheel arches and premium road presence.

Interior & Features: Large 10.25-inch touchscreen, full-digital instrument cluster, ventilated seats, ambient lighting with 64 colour options, premium upholstery and an Infinity sound system with Dolby Atmos.

Engines & Variants: Available with Smart Hybrid petrol, Strong Hybrid, and CNG options. Gearbox choices include manual, automatic, eCVT and even AWD in select trims.

Safety & Tech: Level-2 ADAS features, 6 airbags, 360-degree camera, high-strength safety platform, and advanced driver assistance features.

Mileage: Class-leading efficiency with strong hybrid delivering over 28 kmpl (claimed) and practical CNG option with an underbody tank for more boot space.

Pricing: Introductory ex-showroom prices start around â‚¹10.5 lakh and go up to nearly â‚¹20 lakh for the top-end strong hybrid variants.

Whether youâ€™re looking for fuel efficiency, premium features, or advanced safety, the Maruti Victoris offers a strong package and is set to shake up the mid-size SUV segment!

title: Car Wash Experiment Exposes Perfect Human Outline #shortsvideo
description:

During a routine car wash, a man decided to run a strange little experiment. He pressed his entire body against his own car and stayed stuck to it just to see what kind of pattern would appear. The worker continued pouring thick foamy soap across the surface, covering the entire vehicle until it was fully buried under bubbles.

But the twist came as soon as the man stepped away â€” everyone around froze for a moment, shocked to see a perfect human-shaped outline printed across the carâ€™s surface. title: Why American Cars Are So Expensive
description:
Cars once promised independence and transportation for all Americans. Now, they are a luxury product that cost about $50,000, nearly 30% higher than just a few years ago. Affordable vehicles, especially those below the price of $20,000, have nearly disappeared. And while Automakers pulled in record profits in 2023, slim margins combined with deep investments into EV batteries, software and other technology is making it hard to produce cars much cheaper. Chinese automakers can, but they're impeded by tariffs and rules. Insiders say that is just a bandage - automakers need to compete.

title: Comparing Different Car Suspension Systems Side by Side
description:
Explore the engineering secrets behind the most talked-about chassis designs in the automotive world. This video provides an in-depth visual comparison between the infamous three-link rear suspension, the flawed but practical torsion beam, and the highly acclaimed well-rounded independent suspension. By observing these systems in action, viewers can see how each structure handles lateral forces and vertical impacts, revealing the distinct characteristics that define a vehicle's handling and comfort. The clear, side-by-side demonstration makes complex mechanical theories easy to understand for every car enthusiast.

Understanding these different architectures effectively solves the mystery of why cars feel so different on the road despite having similar specs. While the three-link setup is often criticized for its minimalist design, the torsion beam remains a resilient choice for space efficiency, and the independent suspension continues to set the standard for balanced performance. This technical demonstration highlights the critical trade-offs in automotive manufacturing, where cost, space, and ride quality must be carefully weighed. Seeing the physical movement of these metal links provides a profound sense of mechanical clarity and a deeper respect for the diverse solutions in modern vehicle engineering.

description:
Volvo dropped a bunch of new cars from a crane; they say it was to help rescue services save lives. Yep, they dropped brand new Volvos from 30 meters high for the greater good. When cars impact the ground at over 80 km/h, the cars get messed up, and rescue services can test out all their cool life saving equipment.

title: FERMATI CON L'AUTO RUBATA, AGGREDISCONO I CARABINIERI, ARRESTATI DUE MAROCCHINI | 21/01/2026
description: A3 NEWS Treviso 21/01/2026 - MONTEBELLUNA - Rubano l'auto ad Alano nel Bellunese ma vengono fermati a Montebelluna. Nella vettura droga e armi. Arrestati due marocchini  ||  Prima hanno tentato la fuga e poi hanno ingaggiato una colluttazione violenta con i carabinieri. Spintoni e gomitate contro i militari dell'arma che li hanno fermati in Piazza Vienna a Montebelluna. In manette sono finiti due cittadini marocchini di 25 e 26 anni residenti a Vedelago e Setteville nel bellunese. I due sono stati intercettati a bordo di una Fiat Uno risultata oggetto di furto consumato la notte precedente ad Alano di Piave in provincia di Belluno ai danni di una donna del posto. I due colti nella flagranza dei reati di resistenza a pubblico ufficiale e concorso in ricettazione dovranno anche rispondere di  porto abusivo di armi od oggetti atti ad offendere e detenzione ai fini di spaccio di sostanza stupefacente. Nel corso dei controlli, uno dei due Ã¨ stato infatti trovato in possesso di due coltelli, due involucri termosaldati di cocaina per un peso complessivo di 0,60 grammi e 450 euro in contanti. Lâ€™autovettura rubata Ã¨ stata recuperata e restituita alla legittima proprietaria. I due sono stati giÃ  rimessi in libertÃ  in attesta di processo. title: Good News: Mossberg Maverick is Now Semi-Auto. But the Bad News...| SHOT Show 2026
description: At SHOT Show 2026, Mossberg International introduced the Maverick SA, a value-focused semi-automatic shotgun designed as a true multi-season workhorse. The Maverick SA is a 12-gauge platform chambered for both 2.75-inch and 3-inch shells with a 6-shot capacity, built to deliver reliable performance at an accessible price point. The lineup includes both classic walnut and durable synthetic stock options, along with an adjustable length-of-pull system that allows fit adjustment from 12.5 to 14.25 inches using removable spacers. Standard features include a gas-operated action, cross-bolt safety at the rear of the trigger assembly, quick-empty bolt release, a 28-inch vent rib barrel with fiber optic front sight, and Mossbergâ€™s Accu-Choke system. This is Mossbergâ€™s take on a straightforward, affordable semi-auto shotgun without unnecessary gimmicks. SHOT Show 2026 coverage.

title: SALONE DI BRUXELLES 2026 | Eccolo TUTTO tra novitÃ  e il ritorno delâ€¦ DIESEL
description:
Dimenticate i padiglioni vuoti, i concept fini a se stessi e i saloni "fuffa" degli ultimi anni dove si vedevano soltanto prototipi elettrici lontani dalla realtÃ . Ho visitato il Salone dell'Auto di Bruxelles e ho scoperto, con grande sorpresa, che Ã¨ forse il miglior evento automobilistico che ho visto negli ultimi tempi. Il motivo Ã¨ semplice: finalmente si Ã¨ tornati a parlare di "prodotto", di auto concrete che la gente puÃ² davvero comprare e guidare, e non solo di sogni a batteria irrealizzabili.

In questo lungo reportage vi porto con me attraverso tutti i padiglioni per analizzare nel dettaglio cosa sta succedendo al mercato auto europeo e globale. Si parte dal Padiglione 1, dominato dall'universo Stellantis, dove tra conferme e novitÃ  spicca quella che per me Ã¨ la regina della concretezza: il nuovo Fiat Qubo L. Un ritorno fondamentale per il marchio, che ripropone un mezzo spazioso, versatile e soprattutto economico (sotto i 22.000 euro) con motorizzazione Diesel. Ãˆ la risposta "da battaglia" e intelligente per le famiglie che cercano sostanza e non fronzoli, capace di sfidare la Dacia Jogger sul suo stesso terreno.

Ma Stellantis non Ã¨ solo Fiat. Vi mostro la nuova Alfa Romeo Giulia Quadrifoglio "Luna Rossa", un capolavoro di ingegneria dove il design serve la performance: grazie a soluzioni aerodinamiche derivate dalla Coppa America, l'auto guadagna 140kg di downforce riducendo il drag. Parliamo anche della Lancia Ypsilon HF, che ha un assetto sorprendente, della Jeep Compass che finalmente adotta un ibrido 4 cilindri (addio 1.2 tre cilindri!), e della Leapmotor B10, una cinese "di gruppo" che punta dritta alla Toyota Yaris Cross con design pulito e range extender. Senza dimenticare Opel, che con la nuova Astra porta in dote una qualitÃ  costruttiva e una tecnologia fari (Intellilux) che fa invidia ai brand premium.

Spostandoci verso la Germania, Mercedes-Benz dÃ  una lezione di pragmatismo. Niente stand "solo elettrico", ma una celebrazione dei motori Diesel OM654 e OM656, propulsori che per efficienza e macinatori di chilometri restano imbattibili. Tra una Classe G CoupÃ© da sogno e una gamma completa, spicca la nuova CLA: un'auto che, pur guardando a Oriente, offre un'efficienza elettrica superiore a Tesla grazie al cambio a due velocitÃ .

C'Ã¨ poi la "Renaissance" francese di Renault, dove il tocco di De Meo Ã¨ evidente. La R5 e la R4 dal vivo emozionano, la Clio restyling Ã¨ aggressiva e l'Alpine A390 GT dimostra che i francesi sanno fare auto bellissime e ben costruite.

Ampio spazio anche al Giappone e alla Corea. Toyota domina la scena con due estremi: da un lato la nuova Aygo Cross (IG Cross) Full Hybrid, una citycar che promette consumi ridicoli, dall'altro il monumentale, nuovo Toyota Hilux. Aggiornato nello stile e nella tecnologia, mantiene il telaio a longheroni e le balestre posteriori per caricare una tonnellata e andare ovunque. Ãˆ la definizione di auto indistruttibile. Vediamo anche la Mazda CX-6e, elettrica sorprendentemente efficiente, e una Hyundai che fa sognare gli appassionati con il possibile ritorno dei motori termici sulla gamma sportiva N.

Infine, il capitolo piÃ¹ spinoso: la Cina. In questo video faccio una distinzione netta e necessaria. Da una parte c'Ã¨ chi innova davvero, come Xpeng, che con la P7 Plus porta in Europa un'ammiraglia tecnologica a 45.000 euro con guida autonoma proprietaria e batterie LFP. Dall'altra c'Ã¨ chi, come BYD, sembra puntare solo su numeri drogati da fondi statali e su un marketing che definirei "squallido", basato sull'attacco ai competitor (come la campagna contro i motori Stellantis) piuttosto che sulla valorizzazione del proprio prodotto.

Un viaggio lungo, onesto e senza peli sulla lingua in un Salone che mi ha ridato speranza: l'Europa dell'auto forse si sta svegliando dall'ubriacatura ideologica per tornare a occuparsi di ciÃ² che conta davvero. Buona visione!

This is the all-new Audi Q3, and Matâ€™s got his hands on one for a full, in-depth review! 

Thereâ€™s no denying thereâ€™s a huge amount of small SUVs available to buy in 2026, so does the new Q3 offer enough to stand out from the crowd? Letâ€™s take a closer look, starting with the design. 

Itâ€™s a bit of a poor start, with the front and the side angle leading the Q3 to feel fairly anonymous. The car we have here is the range-topping edition, so it comes with extra black plastic on the front bumper, as well as a more aggressive grille, but the entry-level model wouldnâ€™t come with these options and would leave a lot to be desired. The new Audi logo appears flat and understated, but thankfully, the sleek headlights lend it a bit of presence. Along the side, this edition of the car has black side mirrors, as well as black window surrounds and roof rails, but it still looks fairly generic. Around the bac,k itâ€™s a different story, with the cool tail light design, as well as a full length light bar, with the shaping of the rear end giving it a bit more presence. 

Step inside, and the Q3 has a quality cabin. There are soft-touch materials throughout, and it generally looks and feels expensive. Thereâ€™s a large swooping infotainment and digital dial screen across the dash, and although it comes with a large bezel, the new infotainment system is generally easy to use. The digital dials also look crisp and sharp, although some of the customisation options arenâ€™t the best. All-in-all, though, the Q3 certainly comes with a much better design on the interior compared to the exterior! 

There are a large number of engines available for the new Q3. The entry-level is a 1.5-litre turbo petrol with 150hp, while thereâ€™s also a 2-litre turbo diesel with the same output. Both of these cars have front-wheel drive only. There are two versions of the 2-litre 4-cylinder turbo, both coming with Quattro all-wheel drive and either 204hp or 265hp. Finally, thereâ€™s a plug-in hybrid, which couples a 1.5-litre turbo petrol with a motor & battery to produce 272hp. 

However, thereâ€™s one key point we havenâ€™t addressed yet. The entry-level Q3 now costs Â£38,000, and if you go for the range-topper with a couple of options added (like we have in this video), you could be spending up to Â£58,000 on this small SUV! So is it worth it? Youâ€™ll need to stick with Mat and see for yourself!

title: Are racing cars ACTUALLY FAST? Aston Martin DRAG RACE
description:
Change your car with Carwow: https://bit.ly/Change-Your-Car-2212

Itâ€™s time for a mega Aston Martin Vantage head-to-head! 

Weâ€™ve got Mat in the V12 Vantage (released in 2010), and heâ€™s going up against a Vantage GT8 and a Vantage GT4 race car! The question is, which Vantage will come out on top? Letâ€™s take a closer look at the stats. 

Starting with the V12 Vantage, it was released in 2010, and itâ€™s powered by a 5.9-litre naturally-aspirated V12 that delivers 517hp and 570Nm. Power is sent to the rear wheels via a 6-speed manually and the car weighs in at 1,680kg. As of today, itâ€™s worth around Â£80,000. 

Up next is the Vantage GT8. Itâ€™s packing a 4.7-litre NA V8, and this produces 446hp and 490Nm. It sends this power to the rear wheels via a 6-speed manual, and it tips the scales at 1,510kg. As of today, itâ€™s worth Â£150,000. 

Then, finally, we come to the Vantage GT4 race car. Itâ€™s powered by the same 4-litre twin-turbo V8 found in the Vantage road car, but the power output is restricted to 476hp and 639Nm. This power is sent to the rear wheels via a 6-speed auto gearbox, and itâ€™s the lightest car here, at 1,500kg. It has a value of Â£250,000. 

So all three cars are pretty evenly matched, but could the oldest car here snatch a win? Thereâ€™s only one way to find outâ€¦ LETâ€™S RACE!

This is the Xiaomi SU7 Ultra! 

Itâ€™s a performance car from China that produces over 1,500hp, despite being on sale in China for only Â£55,000! With that in mind, is this the best value-for-money performance car in the world?! Letâ€™s take a closer lookâ€¦

In terms of the design, thereâ€™s no denying the SU7 Ultra looks pretty striking on the road, especially in this yellow paint! Up front, it looks pretty aggressive with a large splitter and air intakes, while along the side, youâ€™ll find carbon fibre sills and side mirrors. Itâ€™s also possible to get a carbon fibre roof as well! Around the back, thereâ€™s a huge wing and an electronically-controlled diffuser. So in performance car terms, it certainly looks the part! 

On the inside, the yellow and black two-tone effect from the outside continues. There may be a few plastic bits within the cabin, but these are easily offset with Alcantara on the steering wheel and roof, as well as carbon fibre on the centre console. Thereâ€™s a rotating digital dial display, a large infotainment screen, and a huge heads-up display. All-in-all, it feels more high-class than a car that costs Â£55,000! 

The entry-level Xiaomi SU7 comes with a single motor that produces 299hp and 400Nm. However, this SU7 Ultra comes with three motors, and they combine to produce an incredible 1,548hp and 1,770Nm - thatâ€™s around 500hp more than a Tesla Model S Plaid! 

So what do you think - is this the best car China has produced to date? Youâ€™ll need to stick with Mat to see for yourself!

The driving feel is authentic and visceral, and crashes are realistic and violent; yet the physics are accessible enough to drive with a keyboard or gamepad while still being authentic with a full racing wheel with uncompromising realism. Environments and vehicles in BNG drive are hand-crafted with passionate attention to detail. With years of meticulous design, research, and experience, we authentically recreate the feeling and excitement of real world driving.

In a world of near total automation, it's nice to slow things down and appreciate the craftsmanship that once went into high end car manufacturing. title: Mitsubishi Lancer EVO 9 & Challenger SRT Hellcat Table-Top Turbo Racing 1:76 Scale | RC ADVENTURES
description:
Busting out the Hellcats and the Lancer Evolution IX from http://www.TurboRacing.net to see what these 1:76 scale racing cars are all about. In the previous video, we looked at the semi-trucks (https://youtu.be/TRwW_IxFzmA?si=SDUmh7RK8icGkAYV) and WOW, if these tiny cars are anything like the haulers, then we are in for a treat!  First, lets get in a quick race with the semi-trucks.. and then unbox this tiny Mitsubishi Lancer Evolution IX and the TWO Dodge Challenger SRT Hellcats.

We are racing literal pocket-sized monsters today â€” Turbo Racingâ€™s micro RC cars in 1:76 scale â€” and these things are way beyond â€œtoy.â€ Theyâ€™ve got full proportional steering and throttle, built-in LiPo batteries, LED lights, and you can drive them on a kitchen table like itâ€™s Le Mans. We put them head-to-head to decide whoâ€™s doing dishes after dinner. Loser washes. Winner talks trash forever.

First up: the red widebody muscle car.
This one is basically a mini Dodge Challenger SRT Hellcat / Demon. You can see it right away: the twin hood scoops, the angry quad headlights in that deep blacked-out grille, the big chin splitter, and those cartoonishly wide fenders. It even has the black racing stripes down the hood. It looks like somebody shrunk a 700+ hp Hellcat down to Hot Wheels size and said, â€œHere, try not to crash this on your cutting board.â€

Second: the red four-door rally beast.
This one is straight-up modeled after a Mitsubishi Lancer Evolution VIII / IX style sedan. Youâ€™ve got the vented hood, the aggressive front bumper, the high-rise rear wing, and that squat AWD rally stance. Itâ€™s got the â€˜we just left a WRC stageâ€™ energy. It LOOKS like it wants to spool a turbo and flame-shoot on downshifts even though itâ€™s smaller than my thumb.

Both cars are Turbo Racing C-series micros (C75 / C76 style). Theyâ€™re 2-wheel drive, 2.4GHz radio, internal LiPo, and theyâ€™ll run for around 20-30 minutes on a charge. The transmitter doubles as a charger, so you literally pull off, pit stop, and youâ€™re back on track. Weâ€™ve got headlights, brake lights, proportional control, and yes â€” they drift and slide around if you push them hard enough. On a tabletop. In your house. This is dangerous because now racing after supper is â€œa thing.â€

Why Iâ€™m freaking out about these:

Theyâ€™re REAL RC cars. Steering isnâ€™t just left/right clicky junk â€” you can feather it.

Theyâ€™re tiny enough to build a racetrack out of whateverâ€™s on your dining table.

The bodies are inspired by actual dream cars. Hellcat attitude vs Evo aggression.

Theyâ€™re stupid fun to crash into your friends with while pretending youâ€™re being â€œtechnical.â€

We tested them side by side, we talked smack, and we found out which one can actually hang through the corners without spinning outâ€¦ and which driver is going to be stuck doing dishes tonight.

Welcome to 1:76 scale chaos. ğŸ”¥

This is why I love RC.

In 1909, Michio Suzuki (1887â€“1982) founded the Suzuki Loom Works in the small seacoast village of Hamamatsu, Japan. Business boomed as Suzuki built weaving looms for Japan's giant silk industry. In 1929, Michio Suzuki invented a new type of weaving machine, which was exported overseas. The company's first 30 years focused on the development and production of these machines.

Despite the success of his looms, Suzuki believed that his company would benefit from diversification and he began to look at other products. Based on consumer demand, he decided that building a small car would be the most practical new venture. The project began in 1937, and within two years Suzuki had completed several compact prototype cars. These first Suzuki motor vehicles were powered by a then-innovative, liquid-cooled, four-stroke, four-cylinder engine. It had a cast aluminum crankcase and gearbox and generated 13 horsepower (9.7 kW) from a displacement of less than 800 cc.

With the onset of World War II, production plans for Suzuki's new vehicles were halted when the government declared civilian passenger cars a "non-essential commodity." At the conclusion of the war, Suzuki went back to producing looms. Loom production was given a boost when the U.S. government approved the shipping of cotton to Japan. Suzuki's fortunes brightened as orders began to increase from domestic textile manufacturers. But the joy was short-lived as the cotton market collapsed in 1951.[11]

Faced with this colossal challenge, Suzuki returned to the production of motor vehicles. After the war, the Japanese had a great need for affordable, reliable personal transportation. A number of firms began offering "clip-on" gas-powered engines that could be attached to the typical bicycle. Suzuki's first two-wheeled vehicle was a bicycle fitted with a motor called, the "Power Free." Designed to be inexpensive and simple to build and maintain, the 1952 Power Free had a 36 cc, one horsepower, two-stroke engine.[12] The new double-sprocket gear system enabled the rider to either pedal with the engine assisting, pedal without engine assist, or simply disconnect the pedals and run on engine power alone.[13] The patent office of the new democratic government granted Suzuki a financial subsidy to continue research in motorcycle engineering.


1955 Suzulight
By 1954, Suzuki was producing 6,000 motorcycles per month and his company had officially changed its name to Suzuki Motor Co., Ltd. Following the success of his first motorcycles, Suzuki created an even more successful automobile: the 1955 Suzuki Suzulight. The Suzulight sold with front-wheel drive, four-wheel independent suspension and rack-and-pinion steering, which were not common on cars until three decades later.

title: Is This the World's First Safety Car?
description:
Step back in time to 1926 to witness one of the most unusual automotive experiments in history! This rare archive footage shows the inventor AndrÃ© Mercier and his "Acrobatic Auto" during a series of controlled tests in France.

Designed with a unique circular chassis, the Mercier car was engineered to be "uncrashable." The goal was to create a vehicle that could roll over and return to its wheels without injuring the driver or destroying the engineâ€”a visionary precursor to the modern roll cage.

This video is shared for historical and educational purposes only. The stunts shown were performed by a professional inventor in a controlled setting for engineering demonstrations nearly 100 years ago. Do not attempt to replicate these maneuvers with modern vehicles.

description:
